The '''''Jolly Darkie Target Game''''' was a game developed and manufactured by the [[McLoughlin Brothers]] (now part of [[Milton Bradley Company]]){{sfn|Congdon-Martin|1990|p=46}} which was released in 1890.{{sfn|Booker|2000|p=124}} It was produced until at least 1915.{{sfn|Washington Afro-American|1986}} 

==Description==
The objective of the game was to throw a wooden ball into a [[Bullseye (target)|bullseye]], the "gaping mouth" of the target in cardboard decorated using imagery of [[Sambo (racial term)|Sambo]]{{sfn|Booker|2000|p=124}}{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=11}} and that could open and close.{{sfn|Tompkins|2012|p=194}} It was one of many products and media of late 19th century in the United States depicting [[African American]]s as "beasts" and associating the black male face Sambo images with [[List of ethnic slurs|racial slur]] terms such as "coon", "darky", "[[nigger]]", and "[[pickaninny]]".{{sfn|Booker|2000|p=124}} Among these was another Milton Bradley game, ''Darky's Coon Game''.{{sfn|Booker|2000|p=124}} The term "darkie" referred to the "exaggerated physiognomic features" depicting black people and associated with [[minstrel show]]s.{{sfn|Jackson|2006|p=23|loc=From minstrel paraphernalia and games to minstrel shows}} In the book ''Ceramic Uncles & Celluloid Mammies: Black Images and Their Influence on Culture'', Patricia Turner reported that she had heard of a black man sitting outside a theatre preceding a minstrel show, with his mouth open and children throwing balls into it for entertainment.{{sfn|Jackson|2006|p=23|loc=From minstrel paraphernalia and games to minstrel shows}} The Cuban poet and journalist [[José Martí]] witnessed a similar scene at [[Coney Island]] and wrote about it.{{sfn|Arroyo|2013|p=199|loc=Note 78}}

It was one of many games produced at the time with a theme involving violence against black people, who were "encountering growing hostility" throughout the United States.{{sfn|Congdon-Martin|1990|p=16}} Another was "Hit the Dodger! Knock him Out!".{{sfn|Congdon-Martin|1990|p=16}} It was also one of the objects produced at the time featuring a mouth and "black ingestion" as a [[Stereotypes of African Americans|stereotype of African Americans]], such as the [[watermelon stereotype]], also exemplified by the "Jolly Nigger Bank" into which coins are inserted into a mouth-shaped slot.{{sfn|Tompkins|2012|p=194}} The target consumer for the game was white people, who bought it for their children.{{sfn|Washington Afro-American|1986}}{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=11}} These games and images reinforced "an encompassing theme of domination" by white people and subordination of black people.{{sfn|Ross Barnett|1982|p=44}} Turner states that such products reflected means by which "American consumers found acceptable ways of buying and selling the souls of black folk" even after the abolition of [[slavery in the United States]], and the use of black images in advertising "figured prominently in commodity capitalism".{{sfn|Hill Collins|2006|p=314|loc=Note 2}}

Today, the game is considered a collector's item.{{sfn|Dant|1999|p=150}} It is part of [[collectable]] black memorabilia, consisting of objects such as dolls, toys, and postcards that include those that are offensive or racist,{{sfn|Washington Afro-American|1986}} even the "most contemptible examples" of such works.{{sfn|Markovich|2000|p=11}} By 1993, there were about 50,000 black memorabilia collectors in the United States, about 70% of whom were African Americans.{{sfn|Gutloff|1993|p=36}}

